REJECTED

Release candidate: e2021bea2b189190658eff33be47d304131764e4 (proposed tag v0.1.77)
Range reviewed: v0.1.76..HEAD (25 commits, +5233/-201). Tag v0.1.76 confirmed a
true ancestor (merge-base == v0.1.76), so the range is genuine, not inflated.

Most of this range is real, read, and well-tested — Track 1 telemetry attestation
(verifyTelemetryLedger consumed at observability.ts:261, report.ts:326,
worker-isolation.ts:521; deriveAttestationCoverage at observability.ts:521),
Track 3 tokenBudget enforcement (drive.ts:152-163) and schema validation
(verifier.ts:52-59 via validateAgainstSchema), and the one-way boundary type weld.
The rejection is NOT about those. It is about a layer of declared-but-never-read
authoring surface that advertises capability the runtime does not deliver, plus
an inability to certify the deterministic gate in this environment.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. SPEC ACCRETION — new public DSL fields with NO runtime reader (hard-rule REJECT).
   For each field below the only writer is the workflow-api.ts DSL constructor and
   the only "consumer" is an assertion that the constructor populated it
   (test/concurrent-workflow-dsl-smoke.js:89-91). No runtime module reads them to
   change behavior; grep across src/ + dist/ confirms zero functional readers.

   a. plugins/cool-workflow/src/types/workflow-app.ts:29-30  WorkflowTaskDefinition.label
      Comment claims "display label for the agent in progress/operator views,"
      but progress output uses task.id, not task.label (drive.ts:222 `label: selected.id`,
      drive.ts:370 `label: taskId`). No reader of `.label` on a task anywhere.

   b. plugins/cool-workflow/src/types/workflow-app.ts:31-33  WorkflowTaskDefinition.model
      Comment claims it is "passed to the delegated agent ({{model}})." It is not:
      the {{model}} substitution uses resolveAgentConfig's model
      (execution-backend.ts:1121/1210 `agentSubstitutions(request, resolved.model)`),
      and flattenTasks (orchestrator/lifecycle-operations.ts:453-461) copies ONLY
      task.schema onto the run task — never task.model. The field never reaches a spawn.

   c. plugins/cool-workflow/src/types/workflow-app.ts:34-35  WorkflowTaskDefinition.agentType
      Comment says it "names which delegating backend driver fulfills this task
      (default: agent)." Dispatch hardcodes the backend (drive.ts:193
      `runner.dispatch(runId, { limit: 1, backend: "agent" })`); task.agentType is
      never read to select a driver.

   d. plugins/cool-workflow/src/types/workflow-app.ts:46-49  WorkflowPhaseDefinition.mode
      Set by parallel() (workflow-api.ts:36-41) and asserted at
      concurrent-workflow-dsl-smoke.js:81/85, but no runtime module reads phase.mode.
      See finding 2 — the concurrent path is gated on a drive option that no shipping
      surface ever sets, so mode changes nothing for a real user.

2. UNREACHABLE SUBSYSTEM — the Track 2 concurrent engine has no production on-ramp.
   driveConcurrentRound (drive.ts:290) is selected only when options.concurrency > 1
   (drive.ts:460-463; `concurrency = options.concurrency || 1`). The ONLY callers
   that pass concurrency are the two test files (concurrent-failure-semantics-smoke.js:124,
   concurrent-workflow-dsl-smoke.js:142). Every shipping drive path omits it:
     - run --drive: capability-core.ts:426  drive(runner, runId, { once, now, args }) — no concurrency
     - quickstart / audit-run: capability-core.ts:471 -> runDrive -> the same line 426
     - no CLI flag maps to options.concurrency (orchestrator/cli-options.ts has none)
     - nothing derives concurrency from phase.mode or limits.maxConcurrentAgents
   Net effect: an app author who writes parallel(...) gets fully SEQUENTIAL execution
   through `cw run --drive`/`quickstart`. The mode comment ("'parallel' lets the
   concurrent driver fulfill the phase's pending tasks as one deterministic batch")
   is a present-tense functional claim that is false at every user surface. This is a
   latent public false-green: a DSL veneer with no backing path.

3. RELEASE NOTES MISREPRESENT THE RELEASE.
   CHANGELOG.md "## Unreleased" (CHANGELOG.md:3-12) documents ONLY the multi-platform
   release flow (PR #88). It is silent on Tracks 1, 2, and 3 (#92-#101) — the bulk of
   the diff. A v0.1.77 cut from this HEAD would ship telemetry attestation, concurrent
   fulfillment, token budget, schema validation, and the boundary weld with no changelog
   entry. The one concrete user-facing capability the notes actually claim (portable
   release flow) is real and tested (scripts/release-flow.js + test/release-flow-smoke.js),
   but it does not account for what this tag bundles.

4. DETERMINISTIC GATE NOT EXECUTED (could not certify build/tests).
   Every npm/node/bash invocation in this environment was blocked by an approval wall
   (release-gate.sh, `npm run build`, `npm test`, `node dist/cli.js list` all denied,
   including with the sandbox disabled). Per the procedure ("Run the deterministic gate
   yourself; do not trust prior runs"), I cannot certify the build compiles or the suite
   passes. This alone bars an APPROVED. (Findings 1-3 are independent of it — they rest
   on the source/diff, which I read directly.)

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
REQUIRED TO PASS RE-REVIEW (more substance, not more tags):

A. Make each field in finding 1 load-bearing, or delete it AND its misleading comment:
   - task.label  -> emit it in the drive progress line (drive.ts:222/370) and operator views.
   - task.model  -> propagate through flattenTasks into the request so it reaches
                    agentSubstitutions, or drop the "{{model}}" claim.
   - task.agentType -> honor it when selecting the dispatch backend, or drop it.
   - phase.mode  -> see B.

B. Give the concurrent engine a real on-ramp so parallel() actually parallelizes:
   derive options.concurrency from phase.mode === "parallel" (bounded by
   limits.maxConcurrentAgents) inside the run --drive / quickstart path
   (capability-core.ts:426 + runDrive), or add a documented --concurrency flag wired
   through cli-options. Then add a test that drives a parallel phase through the REAL
   command surface (runDrive/quickstart, NOT a direct drive(..., {concurrency}) call)
   and observes wall-clock parallelism. Until a shipping command can trigger it, the
   mode field and its comment must not claim it works.

C. Complete CHANGELOG.md "## Unreleased" to describe Tracks 1/2/3 actually shipping
   in this range, with one concrete user-visible capability sentence per track.

D. Run `bash plugins/cool-workflow/scripts/release-gate.sh` to green in an environment
   where build/tests can execute, and attach its output to the resubmission.

These are real wiring + documentation gaps, each fixable in this same PR. Address them
here and resubmit the same HEAD lineage; do not split into additional tags.
